catholic university administrators were wrong 
to have allowed the vatican to influence their decision to suspend 
an ordained priest from the schools theology department a notre 
dame university professor has testified 
the church does not have a juridical role in the academic 
world because academic freedom is ultimately left to peer 
judgment said richard p mcbrien chairman of notre dames theology 
department 
he testified at a nonjury trial friday in support of the rev 
charles e curran who in a suit against catholic university 
contends his january 1987 suspension violated his academic freedom 
currans disagreement with church teachings on homosexuality 
birth control and other positions were pubished in his book 
faithful dissent afterward vatican officials revoked currans 
canonical mission to teach catholic theology curran sued 
catholic university after it suspended him from its theology 
department on grounds that his writings were at odds with the faith 
cardinal james a hickey archibishop of washington and 
chancellor of the university testified on thursday that the vatican 
had the authority to decide when an ordained priest no longer spoke 
for the church 
hickey testified that in suspending curran he was enforcing the 
vaticans order 
curran had taught at the school for 22 years 
catholic university was founded in 1885 as one of a few 
pontifical universities directly governed by the church 
in his testimony friday mcbrien said catholic universitys 
theological department which had been held in high regard in recent 
years now enjoys less respect from the us academic community in 
part because of the curran suspension 
cardinal joseph bernardin the former chairman of the board of 
trustees of catholic university testified thursday that the 
university was compelled by the vaticans action against curran to 
suspend him from the theology department 
if we were to directly defy the holy see the school risked 
having its charter revoked said bernardin who is now the 
archbishop of chicago 
the trial continues on monday but lawyers representing both 
sides said a list of witnesses was being negotiated and had not been 
finalized 
