<TEXT>
the american civil liberties union filed a lawsuit 
against the city friday accusing housing officials of systematic 
warrantless searches of tenants and their visitors in an effort to 
crack down on drug selling 
chicago housing authority officials later agreed to relax some of 
the security rules but the lawsuit was not withdrawn from us 
district court said agency spokeswoman katie kelly 
the lawsuit stems from a security crackdown by the housing 
agency which is trying to evict squatters and violent gang members 
who use the projects as havens for drug deals 
the lawsuit seeks to stop searches of tenants and their 
apartments and to establish reasonable regulations on visits by 
family members and other guests 
under the existing regulations all guests of residents in the 
building have to sign in with the guard at the front door and show a 
piece of valid identification ms kelly said 
the policy has been that guests are asked to leave the building 
at midnight and are not allowed in until 9 am she said 
no overnight guests are allowed unless the tenant has received 
prior approval 
the lawsuit says housing officials and police have 
indiscriminately detained and searched tenants persons and homes 
going through drawers closets personal effects and other items 
these searches have been carried out without the consent of the 
tenants and any prior notice if tenants object they have been 
threatened with arrest the aclu said in a statement 
the lawsuit cites the case of a tenant who was forced to find 
another babysitter for her sisters children after housing officials 
ordered the children out of her apartment at midnight 
under the new rules the guest upon entry will identify him or 
herself to cha personnel but will not need a piece of 
identification although the tenant must confirm that the person is 
a guest ms kelly said 
overnight visitors would be issued guest cards and residents 
could have longterm guests for a period of up to two weeks 
ms kelly said the aclu planned to present the proposals to the 
plaintiffs and planned further discussions with the city 
our intent in all our security procedures is to provide for the 
safety and welfare of our residents and that will continue to be our 
objective she said 
the defendants are the housing agency the city and police 
superintendent leroy martin 
</TEXT>
