<TEXT>
the 516 millionperplane pricetag for the b2 
stealth bomber makes it the most expensive aircraft ever built but 
air force secretary edward c aldridge says whatever the 
radarevading plane costs its worth it 
the stealth bomber which resembles a huge tailless manta ray 
is expected to make its first flight early next year but will not be 
ready for wartime use until 1992 at the earliest aldridge said 
friday 
aldridge told a news conference the design development and 
construction of 132 planes was expected to cost 681 billion by the 
time production ends in mid1995 
expressed in terms of the original estimate the price tag has 
grown from 366 billion to 425 billion in fiscal 1981 dollars 
an increase of about 16 percent aldridge said those figures do not 
reflect cost increases caused by inflation since 1981 or that 
projected in future years 
congress must authorize and appropriate money for production and 
the figures assume it will do so at the pace the air force proposes 
aldridge said a stretchout of production would boost the perplane 
cost by 20 percent or more 
the air force gave the public its first glimpse of the aircraft 
at a ceremony in palmdale calif last month 
about onethird of the total cost of the longrange bomber is 
being spent on research and development the actual production cost 
amounts to 305 million per plane aldridge said 
whatever it costs its worth it aldridge said how much 
is deterrence worth 
this thing is a significant contributor to the strategic 
deterrence of our country the soviets know it they know the 
capabilities this aircraft can provide 
aldridge reviewing the results of a longrunning internal review 
of the b2 said the air force had decided to slow production of the 
bomber during the early years of the program and to accelerate 
production at the end 
he refused to offer specific numbers but he said the 
acceleration at the end of the program would be such that production 
of all 132 of the planes would be completed a year early in 
mid1995 
the latest cost projection includes estimated savings of about 3 
billion the secretary continued thanks to the changes in 
production and a decision to purchase more than 100 of the planes 
under a single multiyear contract 
few of the planes will be built while the bomber is undergoing 
flight testing in the early years aldridge explained once the 
flight testing is completed and the design frozen a multiyear 
contract can be negotiated to achieve the most economical rate of 
production he added 
aldridge said a large portion of the cost increase about 1 
billion in fiscal 1981 dollars results from a major redesign 
effort in 1983 
the air force secretary said the redesign was ordered because the 
stealth bomber originally was meant only to fly at high altitude 
the air force decided in 1983 that the plane should be able to fly 
at low altitude as well and that forced a redesign of its flying 
wing shape he said 
the b2 gets its stealth name from the claim that it will be 
extremely difficult to detect by enemy radar due to the extensive 
use of exotic composite materials its lack of sharp surface angles 
and a crosssection that offers a very small profile to radar it is 
built mainly by northrop corp 
at 516 million per copy the b2 would eclipse the new b1b 
bomber which cost about 280 million per copy as the most 
expensive plane in the air force inventory the newest model of the 
largest us commercial aircraft the boeing 747 sells for roughly 
125 million 
aldridge appearing before pentagon reporters on his last day in 
office before joining the mcdonnell douglas corp said the b2 
would fly for the first time as soon as its ready probably 
early next year 
he said the first operational b2 would be delivered to whiteman 
air force base mo in mid1991 and that the air force probably 
will select three additional bases to house them 
it probably will be at least 1992 before the plane is certified 
for initial operational capability meaning it could fly in a 
war aldridge said 
