police allowed a few relatives and friends of the 29yearold 
editor of the mirror to see his plane off at the airport in maseru 
the capital of lesotho a mountainous kingdom surrounded by south 
africa 
we have allowed him to stay in the country temporarily until 
he can find some place to go an immigration officer in nairobi 
said speaking on condition of anonymity 
maseko said in a telephone interview from the airport in nairobi 
that he wants to go to south africa to join his father he said he 
was born in the indian ocean port of durban and i have many 
relatives there 
maseko claims he is a lesotho citizen through his parents were 
working across the border when he was born he fled south africa in 
1980 after becoming involved in antiapartheid organizations 
police in lesotho said maseko is a south african refugee 
under an agreement with the un high commissioner of refugees 
the lesotho government does not send south african refugees back to 
their homeland or allow them to remain in lesotho they are sent to 
a third country 
the mirror which began publishing in mid1988 is an independent 
weekly 
lesotho is ruled by a sixman military council in association 
with king moshoeshoe ii which took power in a january 1986 coup 
after ousting a leftwing dictator chief leabua jonathan 
all political activity is banned in lesotho 
masekos troubles began in november after he published articles 
stating that minister of finance evaristus sekhonyana who held the 
same portfolio in the jonathan government had authorized the 
transfer of millions of rands to the swiss bank account of an 
italian construction company banco which had failed to finish a 
building project in 1981 the directors of the company had fled 
lesotho and the government liquidated the company 
maseko was detained under the internal security act which allows 
temporary detention of people considered a threat to lesothos 
national security when he appealed to the supreme court for release 
on the ground that he posed no such threat he was charged with 
criminally defaming the finance minister 
when that charge was dropped the head of the military council 
maj gen metsing lekhanya authorized an extension of his detention 
maseko claimed that the secretary to the military council tom 
thebane visited him and warned him about writing articles about 
government officials 
the paper has continued to be published by local journalists but 
its articles are widely regarded as less controversial 
</TEXT>
