<TEXT>
the energy department may have to shut more 
nuclear weapons facilities because president reagan is not proposing 
enough money to operate them in accordance with safety and 
environmental laws the washington post said in its sunday editions 
the newspaper cited a letter in which energy secretary john s 
herrington warned the administration that the proposed 1990 budget 
fell short by 360 million 
i must in good conscience advise you that the system will 
in all likelihood be operating beyond the bounds of acceptable 
risk herrington said in the dec 9 letter to white house chief of 
staff kenneth m duberstein 
spokespersons for the energy department and the white house were 
not available for comment after the story appeared 
according to the post the letter contains a detailed assessment 
of the energy departments budgetary problems which herrington said 
may require choosing between upgrading plant safety and meeting the 
defense departments production goals for nuclear materials 
if the department gives priority to production goals the paper 
quoted herrington then unresolved environmental and safety issues 
are likely to lead to further shutdowns in the weapons complex 
herringtons letter cites years of budget austerity combined with 
the reagan military buildup that put more demands on the system 
part of todays problem stems from our attempts to stretch 
defer and absorb budgetary shortfalls hoping that next year things 
would be better and we could catch up the post quoted herrington 
as a result the countrys ability to produce and maintain a 
nuclear weapons stockpile is in serious jeopardy herrington said 
in the letter the risk is great that without a significant 
increase in resources over the next five years we will no longer be 
able to sustain a strong nuclear deterrent in which we have invested 
57 billion since 1980 
the energy department which operates 17 weapons plants has 
proposed spending 50 billion in the next 20 years to build new 
facilities and correct the most pressing environmental problems 
herrington told duberstein his department would pay for 200 
million in upgrades at its savannah river plants in south carolina 
by using the last of a contingency fund he said the action will 
reduce the fund to zero and leave no cushion for emergencies 
in addition the department has said it will help clear up a 
nuclear waste problem endangering the operation of the denverarea 
rocky flats plant which handles plutonium 
herringtons letter according to the post indicated the 
department is in line for a 900 million budget increase next year 
more than 8 percent higher than its current 12 billion budget the 
secretary said the problems at savannah river and rocky flats will 
result in a 360 million shortfall according to the post 
